<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870825-0068 </DOCNO><HL> Boeing Unit to MakeTruck-Based VersionOf Stinger Air Defense</HL><DD> 08/25/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> BA ALD TXT GTE TRR ROK HRSDEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF) </IN><DATELINE> WASHINGTON  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Boeing Aerospace Co., a unit of Boeing Co., won a $16.2 million Army contract for truck-mounted Stinger air defense systems.    The contract awarded yesterday includes options for 253 additional units over four years, which could raise the contract value to $189.8 million.    The Stinger missile also is a shoulder-fired weapon, and reportedly has been used effectively by Afghan rebels against Soviet aircraft. The truck-based version is expected to expand uses of the missile, and the Pentagon is expected to seek as much as $1 billion to purchase these units over the next decade.    In other contracts, Bendix Field Engineering Corp., a unit of Allied-Signal Inc., won a $21.1 million Navy contract for maintenance of equipment on ships.    Avco Lycoming Textron, a unit of Textron Inc., won a $20.3 million Army contract for engines for M-1 tanks.    Hawaiian Telephone Co., a unit of GTE Corp., won a $20 million Army contract to upgrade communications systems in Japan, including Okinawa.    Tracor Inc. won Air Force contracts totaling $18.5 million for chaff for B-52 aircraft.    Rockwell International Corp. won a $12.5 million Air Force contract for electronic circuits.    Harris Corp. won an $11.2 million Air Force contract for computer equipment. </TEXT></DOC>